# Endure – Core Gameplay Loop (v2)

## What Endure Is

Endure is a fantasy experience where real-world physical effort causes mythic identity to emerge through the player's body.

There are no stat items. There is no mechanical power to acquire. What the player becomes is a consequence of what they have endured — not what they have equipped. The world responds to the player's history. The hold they build reflects the path they walked. The identity that emerges from sustained effort is not a reward. It is a recognition.

Every session answers one question: did you show up?

The answer is always yes, if you did.

---

## The Loop

A new player enters Endure as a Traveler — unmarked, untested, and without declaration. The Traveler is not asked to choose an identity. They are offered four activities at the start: one for each path of endurance. These are not options to be optimized. They are an orientation. A glimpse of what each path feels and costs and asks of the body.

Over the first several sessions, the Traveler simply endures. The game watches. Visual identity begins to surface during this phase — not as an unlocked cosmetic, but as a consequence of what the player is actually doing in the world. The path starts finding its shape before the player names it.

After approximately five activities, the game recognizes what the player's behavior has begun to suggest. Class identity is not declared. It surfaces through a weighted behavioral record that accumulates every time the player commits to an activity. Early sessions carry weight — but less than sustained long-term patterns. The scale never resets. Absence does not move it. Returning after time away does not erase what was built.

---

Before each activity, the player commits. They choose what they will do, how hard they will push, and how long they intend to endure. The commitment is honest — precision tracking is not the point. Trust is. The session begins.

While the player endures in the real world, the game acknowledges presence. At irregular, quiet intervals during longer efforts, low-probability loot moments occur. These are not designed to interrupt focus or create anticipation. They are the game noticing that the player is still here. The drops skew toward commons. Most will become resources. That is their purpose.

When the session ends, the primary loot moment resolves. This carries more weight. The floor is uncommon. Rares, epics, and mythics are possible. Loot in Endure falls into four categories — Blueprints, Aesthetics, Environment, and Junk. Consumables are a fifth distinct category. They arrive alongside the primary loot moment as additive drops, separate from the main pool. They are not part of the loot table. They are invitations toward a path — never assignments.

---

The player reviews what was earned and resolves each item. Every piece of loot has two valid outcomes: use it, or destroy it.

The four main categories are Blueprints, Aesthetics, Environment, and Junk. None of these categories affect mechanical power. All gear is aesthetic. A Blueprint unlocks something the player can build in their hold. Aesthetics express identity. Environment enriches the world. Junk converts cleanly into resources. Destroying any loot is not failure. It is authorship — the player deciding what stays and what becomes something else.

Resources are what endurance leaves behind when loot is not wanted. They flow entirely through the loot pipeline. There are no direct drops. Resources fund Hold construction — the primary and most significant thing they do — and earned marks, where the player commits a tattoo, scar, or ritual symbol to permanent expression on the character. Cosmetic expression is always free and reversible. Earned marks are different: they are memory given form. Resources are the ritual cost of permanence.

---

The hold is the player's sanctuary. It begins empty. It comes alive through Blueprint-funded construction, filled over time with a clan — people moving, gathering, building habit and rhythm in the space the player has shaped. The hold does not merely reflect who the player is. It accumulates who the player was. Structures built during an earlier identity phase carry that phase's visual and thematic weight. The hold does not update retroactively. It holds the record.

XP marks what happened. After the minimum completion criteria are met, XP is always awarded. It scales with effort. It never decays. It never punishes absence. It is not random. If the player showed up, the session moved their character forward. This is not conditional.

---

As the player endures more demanding activities, harder tiers become available — not because a power threshold was crossed, but because the player is doing harder things in the real world. Activity tiers respond to real effort. They do not respond to identity status or accumulated mechanical advantage. All players access harder content the same way: by enduring it.

Identity deepens through sustained behavior. If the player's activity history reflects meaningful overlap between two paths — over time, through honest effort — the game begins to recognize something. A hybrid identity surfaces. It is not selected, not unlocked, not a tier to be achieved. It is a reflection of what the player's body has been doing.

All ten identities — the four base classes and the six hybrids — are peers. Each has its own Blueprint pool. Access to any pool requires behavioral alignment with that path. The mechanism is identical across all ten. There is no hierarchy. There is only recognition.

---

The loop repeats. Each session is its own act of endurance. Each adds to the record. The hold becomes more itself. The player becomes more themselves.

The player is not working out.

They are playing Endure.

---

## One-Line Summary

Enter as a Traveler, commit to effort, let sustained behavior determine the identity that surfaces — endure in the real world, earn guaranteed XP, resolve loot into expressions and resources, build a hold that holds your history, and unlock harder paths by doing harder things.
